column5: For solving the connectivity problem we use Quick-find which is also called eager approach. Here the data structure we use is an integer array and the interpretation is the two objects p and Q are connected if they have the same id. If we look at the code we take an individual private array named id and in the constructor quick find UF we are setting id of each object to it self. Then we have a method called connected which is used to check whether the given two inputs i.e, p and q are under same component or not and  returns a boolean value. We have another method called union which is used to change all the entries with id[p] to id[q]. Then we have to find how efficient the algorithm is. This takes N^2 array accesses to process sequence of N union commands on N objects. This is problematic because the union function is too expensive.

column5:
To link up all the elements in an array of size n, it takes upto (n^3 - n^2) / 2 operations. The first operation will iterate through the entire array and link up each element with itself. The second operation will link up with every element except the first, the third element with every other element except for both the first and second, and so on.... 
So suppose the array has one element, there will be no operations since there is no other element for that one to link up with. 
Suppose the array has two elements, to link up both of them it will take one operation and for a three element array, it will take up to three operations.
The sequence is as follows:
No. of elements            No of operations
1                                      0
2                                      1
3                                      2 + 1 = 3
4                                      3 + 2 + 1 = 6
.                                       .
.                                       .  
.                                       .
n                                      (n-1) + (n - 2) + (n -3) + ........ + 1 = (n)(n-1) / 2

To access each element, the array has to be iterated throughout once, hence the total no of operations taken will be
(n) ( n^2 - n) / 2
So the total operation considering an algorithm which links up each element of an array of size n with every other element without following any assumptions takes up to (n^3 - n^2) / 2.

similarly for N=4, total pairs = 6 pairs
therefore for N elements there are NC2 pairs or (N^2-N)/2
and for each pair it takes N steps for making the union. Therefore total steps are: (N^3-N^2)/2 and complexity: O(((N^3-N^2)/2) (for smaller values of N)
else for larger values of N: complexity=O(N^3)

column5: This is about dynamic connectivity. To solve dynamic connectivity problems we use two algorithms Quick find and Quick union and we also go through applications and improvements of those algorithms. We have some steps to develop an usable algorithm. They are "model the problem, find an algorithm to solve it, check whether it is fast enough, whether it fits in memory or not. If not we have to find the reason for it. Then we have to find a way to solve the problem and find a new algorithm and iterate it until it is satisfied. Let's consider if we are given N objects then union command is used to connect two objects and find query is used to find  out is there a path connecting the two objects. This algorithm is used in applications like pixels in a digital photo, friends in a social network etc. There are few properties that the connections need to satisfy.Generally we assume that "is connected to is an equivalent relation i.e every object connected to itself is symmetric i.e, if p is connected to q, then q is connected to p and it is transitive i.e if p is connected to q and q is connected to r, then p is connected to r".To implement the operations we have to know two things "Find query and union component".Find query is used to check if two objects are in the  same component and union command is used to replace components containing two objects with their union.

--> Rough standard..10^9 operations per second, 10^9 words of main memory.

column5:
Dynamic connectivity . The input is a sequence of pairs of integers, where each integer represents an object of some type and we are to interpret the pair p q as meaning p is connected to q. We assume that "is connected to" is an equivalence relation:
symmetric: If p is connected to q, then q is connected to p.
transitive: If p is connected to q and q is connected to r, then p is connected to r.
reflexive: p is connected to p.
Dynamic connectivity has major applications.

column5: Quick-find algorithm is an approach to solve Dynamic connectivity problem. Major operations are discussed in the video "union", "find" and "connected"."Union" operation connects two nodes and "find" method retrieves the id value of that node in the array. The connected method checks whether the two given nodes are connected are not.Quick-find algorithm is quicker to identify whether two nodes are connected are not because "find" method has O(1) time complexity.It is implemented using one array which has its corresponding indexes as values.If we connect two nodes in the graph using "union" method the array values of nodes having a value equal to the first node are changed to second node value.The nodes having same array values are said to be connected. We can check the connectivity status of two nodes easily in the Quick-Find algorithm.At the same time for each pair, "union" operation takes O(N) time. The time complexity becomes O(N^2) for N pairs.

column5:
In dynamic connectivity, we can use quick find algorithm to find connectivity between nodes. First get the value for each index location of an array. Then go by the operations given as input by the user. For each operation, perform all the four functions: find, connected, count, union. 
Find: gives the index location of element
Connected: check if two element values match
Count: give the number of combined parts in array
Union: If two nodes are not connected, change the values of all locations which have values equivalent to value at first index, with value at second location.

column5:
QUICK FIND:

--> Integer array id[] of size N.
--> Interpretation: p and q are connected if they have the same id.
--> Find : Check if p and q have the same id.
-->Union : To merge components containing p and q, change all entries with id[p] to id[q].
DISADVANTAGES:

QUICK FIND IS TOO SLOW:

--> Quick find algorithm may take M*N steps to process M union commands on N Objects.
--> Rough standard..10^9 operations per second, 10^9 words of main memory.
--> Quadratic algorithms get worse with newer equipment.

column5:
Dynamic Connectivity:

-->The set of N objects are given.
PART 1: Union command-Connect two objects
PART 2: Find/Connect test - Is there a path between the two objects?


Applications involve manipulating objects of all types:

1)Computers in network
2)Friends on social network
3)Transistors in computer chip
4)Pixels in digital photo

When programming, convenient to name objects 0 to N-1:

1)Use integers in array index.
2)Suppress details not relevant to union-find.

"is connected to":
1) Reflexive: p is connected to q
2) Symmetric: p==q <==> q==p
3) Transitive: p==q ==> q==r ==> p==r

Connected components: maximum set of components connected.

Union-find Data Type(API):

"public class UF"

UF(int N) --> Intialize N objects

void union(int p, int q) --> add connection b/w p&q.

boolean connected(int p, int q)--> p&q are in the same component?

int find(int p) --> component identifier(0 to N-1)

int count() -->Number of components.

PROBLEM:

Read N objects, pair of objects as input, if they are not connected,connect them and print out pair.

Program for dynamic connectivity:
public class UnionFind{
public static void main(String[] args){
int N = StdIn.readInt(); //number of elements
UF uf = new UF(N);
while(!StdIn.isEmpty()){
int p = StdIn.readInt(); //input first element
int q = StdIn.readInt(); //input second element
if(!uf.connected(p,q)){
uf.union(p,q); //connect both the elements
StdOut.println(p+" "+q); //output
}
}

} 
}

UNION FIND OR DYNAMIC CONNECTIVITY:

Steps to develop a usable algorithm:

1)Try to understand the main elements of the problem.
2) Find an algorithm to solve it.
3) Is it fast enough? Does it fit in the memory?
4) If not...why?
5) How to address the problem?
6) Iterate the above steps until satisfied.

Dynamic Connectivity:

-->The set of N objects are given.
PART 1: Union command-Connect two objects
PART 2: Find/Connect test - Is there a path between the two objects?


Applications involve manipulating objects of all types:

1)Computers in network
2)Friends on social network
3)Transistors in computer chip
4)Pixels in digital photo

When programming, convenient to name objects 0 to N-1:

1)Use integers in array index.
2)Suppress details not relevant to union-find.

"is connected to":
1) Reflexive: p is connected to q
2) Symmetric: p==q <==> q==p
3) Transitive: p==q ==> q==r ==> p==r

Connected components: maximum set of components connected.

Union-find Data Type(API):

"public class UF"

UF(int N) --> Intialize N objects

void union(int p, int q) --> add connection b/w p&q.

boolean connected(int p, int q)--> p&q are in the same component?

int find(int p) --> component identifier(0 to N-1)

int count() -->Number of components.

PROBLEM:

Read N objects, pair of objects as input, if they are not connected,connect them and print out pair.

Program for dynamic connectivity:
public class UnionFind{
public static void main(String[] args){
int N = StdIn.readInt(); //number of elements
UF uf = new UF(N);
while(!StdIn.isEmpty()){
int p = StdIn.readInt(); //input first element
int q = StdIn.readInt(); //input second element
if(!uf.connected(p,q)){
uf.union(p,q); //connect both the elements
StdOut.println(p+" "+q); //output
}
}

} 
}

column5: This video explains one of the possible algorithms to solve dynamic connectivity. 'Quick find' is an algorithm which implements an id array such that all the connected elements have same id. This algorithm has constant time complexity to find the connectivity between two points as the function returns true if both of the components have same ids. However, time complexity to perform union operation may go up to n*n in the worst case, as we have to make all the ids corresponding to p,q equal. Quadratic complexity algorithms are not acceptable in this era where we deal with huge memory hence it is always preferred to write efficient algorithms which consume less time.

column5:
- In this lecture, the lecturer discussed a method for solving the dynamic connectivity problem, called Quick Find or eager approach.
- The data structure used here is, integer array where the indices are the objects and the values in the respective indices are used to find the connectivity and to make connections.
- If the values in the indices p and q are same, then they are connected else, they are not connected.
- In order to make connections between p and q, the values in the index q must be equal to the value in the index p and all the indices values which are equal to the previous value of index p must be changed to the value in index p.
- However, in this approach, the time complexity is O(N^2), which is not beneficiary for larger values on N.

column5:
- In order to solve the dynamic connectivity problems the lecturer introduced to solve this problem by 2 classic algorithms which are 1. Quick Find and 2. Quick Union.
- Discussed the steps foe developing a usable algorithm
- Discussed the dynamic connectivity of the problem(model of the problem)
     Given a set of N objects
     Union command: Connects two objects
     Find/Connected Query: Checks whether there is a path between the two objects
- Assumptions in treating "is connected to" as an equivalence relation:
     -Reflexive: p is connected to p
     -Symmetric: if p is connected to q, then q is connected to p
     -Transitive: if p is connected to q and q is connected to r, then p is connected to r.
- Connected components: Maximal set of objects that are mutually connected.
- For implementing the operations, there are two operations they are:
     Find Query: Check if the two objects are in the same component
     Union command: Replace components containing two objects with their union.
- Discussed an algorithm of Union-Find, where there is a UF data structure with N objects and there are two methods in the UF class, which are 1. union which takes integers p and q as arguments and adds connection to it and 2. connected which takes integers p and q as arguments and checks whether they are connected or not and returns True if they are connected, else returns False.

column5:
Quick find is one solution to the union-find problem. The main concept of this algorithm is that we use an array to keep track of connections. The array is indexed by the object number i.e., if we have N objects, then we would have an array of length N, with each object 0 represented by array index 0 and so on.
When we have a union command between two objects, the two corresponding indices would be set to an equal value (the ID of one of the objects). For a find query, we just check if the indices corresponding to the two objects contain equal values.
This algorithm does provide a solution but the operations of constructing the array (initialization) and updating the array (union) take linear time to complete, since they have to run through the entire array once. This is not very efficient when presented either with a large number of objects, or a large number of union operations, or both.

The overall lecture went very well. I learnt about different types of data types, learnt about abstract data types in detail and
also learnt about different types of memory we have, how to store data in it and access the data in memory. I also learnt different data
structure and how to use them for different problems. I got to know that we have to write a code in a most optimized way so that the code 
works in an efficient way. 
The different data types we have are bit, byte, short, int, float, char, long, double etc. User defined data types are 
abstract data types. Mainly there are two types of memories which are in built in a computer. They are RAM and ROM. Random access memory(RAM)
can be used to access data quickly. When we ckeck for data at a specific location the memory controller directs the location of
the required data in a RAM whithout searching. But in Read only memory(ROM), the data that is to be accessed should be searched through out
the ROM. That is why RAM is quicker than ROM. Data structure can be used only by creating space in the memory. So when we use data
structure, memory plays a vital role in it. Different data structures we have are arrays, linked lists, trees, hashmaps etc. Arrays
can be used by creating space in the memory. We have dynamic arrays also. Liked lists are used using pointers. Trees can be used using 
pointers and by many other methods.
At the end of the class I learnt about the above given information.

column5:
We discussed about the data storage.i.e.,about the RAM-random access memory. The data can be searched, sorted, remove elements, add elements etc. We can perform many such operations on the data. The data types are bit, byte, integer, character, string etc.

There are abstract data types like array lists, queues, stacks, linked lists, hashmaps etc. where we need to operate the data in many ways. The memory is searched by the processor in the ram where it directly fetches the data. The searching is based on the Big-Oh notations.The fastest processing is done by the registers and cache. Whereas, the cloud is the slowest.

The smallest data storage is "bit". 8 bits = 1 byte.
The integer data type can store about 256 integers.i.e., (0-255).Whereas, the negative integer can store only 7 bits and 1 bit is used for storing the sign(-) and the decimals are stored in the same way but, the numerical and integral part in the different memory locations.

When it comes to array storage, the memory allocation is searched based on the number of elements and the size of the data type.
for eg: if we have to store 10 integers, we have to search for size of integer data type = 4 bits, number of integers = 10 ...i.e., 40 bits.

The hashmaps contain keys and values.The hashmaps are not useful all the times,if the keys are not uniformly distributed..i.e., Unique keys may contain unique indices and the value for the particular key will not change even if it is different.

4.1 Write a summary of your learning from this video.
column5:
The lecture describes the union-find problem: given a set of objects, either create connections between objects with the union command, or check whether two objects are connected with the find (or connected) query.
To do this, according to the lecture, we need to maintain what are called connected components. Connected components are subsets of the given set of objects that are connected. Intuitively speaking, we would start out with N connected components with one element each, where N is the number of elements (objects) in the set. As we keep adding unions between objects, we should merge the respective connected components. This, according to the lecture, would make our program efficient. I would argue that that would depend on the algorithm we would be using to merge connected components and search inside a connected component for an object.

0

then the sets would be
{0}
{1 2 3}
{4 5 6 7}
if you say union(3,4) then the sets should be
{0}
{1 2 3 4 5 6 7}

column4: 2.2 Give your rating for the orientation class on Algorithms and Data Structures
2.1 Write a summary of your learning from the class
column5:
1. Order of access speed for Memory: Register>Cache>ROM>RAM>HDD>Cloud.
2. Cache picks the whole memory block to operate and thus is faster than RAM.
3. RAM is faster than HDD because, memory addresses can be accessed directly from RAM without going over each address.
4. Array when initiated gets a chunk of memory according to Data Type and number of elements in array. All elements are in a order in memory.
5. Resizing is of O(n), allocates new block of memory, copies the previous entries and free the previous memory.
6. Array of pointers can be used to store elements at random memory locations and their addresses are stored in the array to operate over them. 
7. Lists are like Dynamic arrays, We can add, remove, sort, search and compare the entries.
8. Linked lists are randomly stored elements with a head as it's own address and tail  pointing to next element by address.
9. HashMaps are Sets of Keys and Values. We can directly access them with their keys. Worst case happens when all values collide with same key and it acts as a array.
10. Array are faster as they are picked into cache and read. rest all are read by their addresses from RAM and are therefore slower than Arrays in the sense of access. But allocation is fixed for arrays where as it's dynamic for the rest of Data Structures we discussed.

column5:
The morning class was about memory allocation, data structures and data types. Data structures is organising data for faster access and storage management. The discussion also included memory management between RAM, cache, HDD and cloud. Cache and registers provide faster memory access. 
The basic data type upon which all the other data types depend is bit. Byte can be formed from 8 bits. Then, there was a discussion about allocating memory for a string and set of strings. There are two ways of setting up memory: 
1. find maximum word length and form array of arrays with it.
2. using pointers to record address
There is memory wastage if we use the first option but the process of accessing the data is quick. In the second option, memory is used appropriately but the process is slower.
There are complexities for each problem as it depends on the programmer and his efficiency.

column4: 2.2 Give your rating for the orientation class on Algorithms and Data Structures
2.1 Write a summary of your learning from the class
column5:
Data structures are a way of organizing the data whereas Algorithms are the step by step process of how we fill the data into data structures. We study algorithms to find the most efficient solution to a particular problem. The time complexities that we use are the following(in the order of their efficiency):
1. constant(O(1))
2.log(O(logn))
3.linear(O(n))
4.loglinear(O(nlogn))
5.Quadratic(O(n^2))
6.cubic(O(n^3))
7.Exponential(O(2^n))
The speed of a data structure depends on its location.
1.Register and Cache faster than Ram
2.RAM- faster because it has access to the memory location
3.HDD
4.Cloud
In case of sequential data structures, the memory blocks are moved to cache when you start to access the first element.
We use the best, average and worst case analysis to find the upper and lower bounds.
